    "body": "@fabricetriboix Hi. Here's a [guide](http://tobyho.com/2015/12/16/mocha-with-promises/) to using asynchronous methods in Mocha. I think you should be able to get the correct execution if you return the promise to mocha, as below:\r\n\r\n```javascript\r\nit('waits for everything to resolve', function(){\r\n  return myAsyncMethod().then(function(){\r\n      return anotherAsyncMethod().then( .... etc .. \r\n})\r\n``` \r\n\r\nAnother approach is to use Mocha's `done` function, which can be passed to the test like this:\r\n```javascript\r\nit('waits for done to be called', function(done){\r\n  myAsyncMethod().then(function(){\r\n     console.log('hello!');\r\n     done();\r\n  });\r\n})\r\n```",
